    Collection specific methods 

1) Method: boolean add(E element)
Purpose :
Adds an element to the collection. Returns true if the collection changed (i.e., the element was added).

2) Method: boolean addAll(Collection<? extends E> c)
Purpose :
Adds all elements from another collection to this collection. Returns true if elements were added.

3)Method: void clear()
Purpose :
Removes all elements from the collection, leaving it empty.

4) Method: boolean contains(Object o)
Purpose :
Checks if the collection contains the specified element. Returns true if found.

5) Method: boolean containsAll(Collection<?> c)
Purpose :
Checks if the collection contains all elements from another collection. Returns true if all are found.

6) Method: boolean isEmpty()
Purpose :
Checks if the collection has no elements. Returns true if it is empty.

7) Method: Iterator<E> iterator()
Purpose :
Provides a way to loop through (or iterate over) the elements of the collection.

8) Method: boolean remove(Object o)
Purpose :
Removes a specific element from the collection. Returns true if it was successfully removed.

9) Method: boolean removeAll(Collection<?> c)
Purpose :
Removes all elements that are also present in another collection. Returns true if any elements were removed.

10 )Method: boolean retainAll(Collection<?> c)
Purpose :
Keeps only the elements that are also present in another collection and removes the rest. Returns true if changes were made.

11) Method: int size()
Purpose :
Returns the number of elements in the collection.

12) Method: Object[] toArray()
Purpose :
Converts the collection into an array of Object type.

13) Method: <T> T[] toArray(T[] a)
Purpose :
Converts the collection into an array of a specific type.

14) Method: boolean equals(Object o)
Purpose :
Checks if this collection is equal to another object.

15) Method: int hashCode()
Purpose :
Returns a hash code for the collection, used in hashing-based data structures like HashSet.

=============================================STREAM API RELATED (LATER)=====================================================
16) Method: Spliterator<E> spliterator()
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Provides a way to split the elements for parallel processing.

17) Method: Stream<E> stream()
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Returns a stream (sequence of elements) to perform operations like filtering and mapping.

18) Method: Stream<E> parallelStream()
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Returns a parallel stream for concurrent operations.
List Specific methods 
Java List Interface Methods

1) Method: void add(int index, E element)
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Adds an element at a specific position (index) in the list.

2) Method: E get(int index)
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Retrieves the element at the specified index in the list.

3) Method: E set(int index, E element)
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Replaces the element at the specified index with a new element.

4) Method: E remove(int index)
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Removes the element at the specified index from the list.

5) Method: int indexOf(Object o)
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Returns the index of the first occurrence of the specified element, or -1 if not found.

6) Method: int lastIndexOf(Object o)
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Returns the index of the last occurrence of the specified element, or -1 if not found.

7) Method: ListIterator<E> listIterator()
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Returns a list iterator to traverse through the elements of the list.

8) Method: ListIterator<E> listIterator(int index)
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Returns a list iterator starting from the specified index.

9) Method: List<E> subList(int fromIndex, int toIndex)
Purpose (Simple Terms):
Returns a portion of the list between the specified indexes (from fromIndex to toIndex).
